Creating Images with R

With a little bit of magick!

Shiwangni Prakash

2023-03-12

My Meme

This is my meme that I created. Since I am Indian, I have found it very useful to learn coding in my own language (Hindi) from YouTube. This is not an original meme, I have seen quite a few of these memes on Social Media so i decided to recreate it.

library(magick)

# creating 2 squares for image and teacher text
first_image <- image_read('bit1.jpg') %>%
  image_scale(200)

teacher_text <- image_blank(width = 125,
                                     height = 125,
                                     color = '#ffffff') %>%
  image_annotate(text = 'Learning coding \n from a teacher',
                 color = '#000000',
                 size = 15,
                 font = 'Impact',
                 gravity = 'center')


# creating 2 more squares for image and friend text
second_image <- image_read('bit2.jpg') %>%
  image_scale(200)

friend_text <- image_blank(width = 125,
                                      height = 125,
                                      color = '#ffffff') %>%
  image_annotate(text = 'Learning coding \n from a friend',
                 color = '#000000',
                 size = 15,
                 font = 'Impact',
                 gravity = 'center')


# creating last 2 squares for image and YouTube text
last_image <- image_read('bit3.jpg') %>%
  image_scale(200)

youtube_text <- image_blank(width = 125,
                                   height = 125,
                                   color = '#ffffff') %>%
  image_annotate(text = 'Learning coding \n from an Indian guy \n on YouTube',
                 color = '#000000',
                 size = 15,
                 font = 'Impact',
                 gravity = 'center')

# creating the rows
top_row <- image_append(c(teacher_text, first_image))
middle_row <- image_append(c(friend_text, second_image))
last_row = image_append(c(youtube_text, last_image))

#putting it all together
meme <- c(top_row, middle_row, last_row) %>%
  image_append(stack = TRUE) %>%
  image_scale(500)
meme
image_write(meme, "my_meme.png")

My Animation

This is the animation that I created. I have noticed that most people struggle to find mistakes within their code and so this is why i created this GIF. Most people come to realize that it was something tiny like a comma that they missed.

library(magick)

# preparing the images that i am going to use
face1 <- image_read('face1.jpg') %>%
  image_scale(500)

face2 <- image_read('face2.jpg') %>%
  image_scale(500)

face3 <- image_read('face3.jpg') %>%
  image_scale(500)

face4 <- image_read('face4.jpg') %>%
  image_scale(500)

# creating first frame
frame1 <- face1 %>%
  image_annotate(text = 'About to start coding',
                 color = '#ffffff',
                 size = 40,
                 font = 'Impact',
                 gravity = 'north')

# creating second frame
frame2 <- face2 %>%
  image_annotate(text = "My code isn't working",
                 color = '#ffffff',
                 size = 40,
                 font = 'Impact',
                 gravity = 'north')

#creating third frame
frame3 <- face3 %>%
  image_annotate(text = "Struggling to find my mistake",
                 color = '#ffffff',
                 size = 40,
                 font = 'Impact',
                 gravity = 'north')

# creating last frame
frame4 <- face4 %>%
  image_annotate(text = "I missed a comma",
                 color = '#ffffff',
                 size = 40,
                 font = 'Impact',
                 gravity = 'north')

# putting the frames together and creating th animation
animation <- c(frame1, frame2, frame3, frame4)

image_animate(animation, fps = 1)

image_write(animation, "my_animation.gif")
